{{Quote box |width=300px |align=right |quoted=true |bgcolor=#CCFFFF |salign=rightIf I forget my native speech, |quote =<poem> '''My Language''' If I forget my native speech And the songs that my people sing What use are my eyes and ears? What use is my mouth?
If I forget the smell of the earth And do not serve it well What use are my hands? Why am I living in the world?
How can I believe the foolish idea That my language is weak and poor If my mother’s last words Were in Evenki? </poem> |source =From ''"Bol moya, Evenkiya"'' Sovetskaya Kultura, July 28, 1988" }} '''Alitet Nikolaevich Nemtushkin''' ([[Irkutsk Oblast]], [[Siberia]] 12 November 1939 - 2006) was an [[Evenks|Evenk]]-Russian poet known for writing in and about his native [[Evenki language]]. He has received wide recognition in and outside of Russia, and his work is used by [[UNESCO]] to cultivate attention to the problem of [[Endangered language|Language Endangerment]] <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.3cworldfiction.com/ififorget.html |title=3C World Fiction |access-date=2012-08-03 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130116055313/http://www.3cworldfiction.com/ififorget.html |archive-date=2013-01-16 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> He has published more than 31 books of poetry, most of them in Russian, but some in Evenki.<ref>Alexia Bloch. 2004. Red Ties and Residential Schools: Indigenous Siberians in a Post-Soviet State. University of Pennsylvania Press. p. 193</ref><ref>[http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0019/001924/192416e.pdf UNESCO 2011. “Atlas of the World’s Languages in Danger”] </ref>
