'''Keith Cowing''' is an astrobiologist,<ref name="CowingSite">{{cite web|url=http://www.cowing.com/|publisher=Cowing.com|title=Keith Cowing, Webmaster, astrobiologist, journalist, former rocket scientist, and recovering ex-civil servant|accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> an American former [[NASA]] employee and the editor of the [[United States|American]] [[Space exploration|space program]] [[blog]] ''NASA Watch''. He is a [[Credential#Journalism|credentialed]] NASA [[journalist]] and is known to be a [[critic]] of NASA activities and [[Policy|policies]].<ref name="CowingSite"/><ref>{{cite web | last=Tolson | first=Mike | title=What would NASA in the age of Trump look like? | website=Houston Chronicle | date=January 7, 2017 | url=http://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/What-would-NASA-in-the-age-of-Trump-look-like-10842673.php | access-date=July 17, 2017}}</ref>

==NASA Watch==
''NASA Watch'' is a website blog which provides insider information and commentary about the United States space program and the U.S. government agency, NASA.<ref name="RJ"/> The first posting was in March, 1996. Cowing is a strong supporter of human spaceflight.<ref name="SpaceStationShine">{{cite web|last1=Crittenden|first1=Jules|date=October 29, 2000|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/bostonherald/access/62997952.html?dids=62997952:62997952&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+29%2C+2000&author=Jules+Crittenden&pub=Boston+Herald&desc=Huge+space+station+set+to+shine&pqatl=google|title=Huge space station set to shine|publisher=[[Boston Herald]]|accessdate=November 14, 2011}}</ref> Cowing started the website when [[Daniel Goldin]] was administrator of NASA and at that time expressed harsh criticism of Goldin's policies. The inciting event for Keith was the mass layoffs in the transition from [[Space Station Freedom]] to the [[International Space Station]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Cowing|first=Keith|date=June 9, 2010|url=http://www.nasawatch.com/archives/2010/06/space-station-f.html|title=Space Station Freedom Deja Vu All Over Again|publisher=Nasa Watch|accessdate=November 14, 2011}}</ref> For several years, NASA refused to accredit Cowing as a journalist and denied him access to NASA media events. Cowing was eventually granted full press accreditation.<ref name="RJ">{{cite web|last=Godin|first=Mary Ellen|date=December 12, 1999|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=38z6pN3vtwoC&dat=19991212&printsec=frontpage&hl=en|title=Keeping an Eye on NASA|publisher=The Record-Journal|accessdate=November 14, 2011}}</ref>

Cowing was a firm supporter of Goldin's successor as administrator, [[Sean O'Keefe]], appointed by [[George W. Bush]]. Cowing also obtained exclusive first-hand information about the genesis of the [[Vision for Space Exploration]], detailed in the book ''New Moon Rising'' which Cowing wrote with Frank Sietzen.<ref name="NewMoon">{{cite book|title=New moon rising : the making of America's new space vision and the remaking of NASA|publisher=[[Apogee Books]]|date=2004|last1=Sietzen|first1=Frank|last2=Cowing|first2=Keith|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/new-moon-rising-the-making-of-americas-new-space-vision-and-the-remaking-of-nasa/oclc/56140988&referer=brief_results|isbn=978-1894959124|accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref>

When [[Michael D. Griffin|Michael Griffin]] was NASA administrator, the relationship between NASA Watch and NASA seemed to have been a more confrontational one. Cowing, as well as other space program insiders, commented negatively about a return to Goldin-style management practices under Griffin.<ref name="CSMon">{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2005/0615/p01s01-usgn.html|title=NASA changes to run deep|date=June 15, 2005|last=Sappenfield|first=Mark|publisher=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]|accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> Cowing dubbed Monday, June 13, 2005 as ''Black Monday'' when many NASA personnel were sent reassignment letters.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cowing|first=Keith|date=June 13, 2005|url=http://nasawatch.com/archives/2005/06/purge-update-1.html|title=Purge Update|publisher=NASA Watch|accessdate=November 16, 2011}}</ref>

