'''Russell David''' "'''Russ'''" '''Roberts''' (born September 19, 1954) is an [[economist]] and a research fellow at [[Stanford University]]'s [[Hoover Institution]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hoover.org/profiles/russell-roberts | title = Russell Roberts profile | publisher = Hoover Institution, Stanford University | access-date = August 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://cafehayek.com/2012/09/joining-hoover-full-time.html | title = Joining Hoover full-time | author = Russ Roberts | publisher = Cafe Hayek | date = 5 September 2012 | accessdate = 24 December 2012}}</ref> He is well known for communicating economic ideas in understandable terms<ref>{{cite news | last = Editorial staff | title = In Praise of . . . EconTalk | newspaper = The Guardian | location = London | date = August 31, 2010 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/sep/01/econtalk-in-praise-of-editorial | access-date = August 6, 2017}}</ref> as host of the ''[[EconTalk]]'' podcast.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://econtalk.org | title = ''EconTalk'', hosted by Russ Roberts | publisher = Library of Economics and Liberty. | quote = Economics podcast for daily life. Weekly interviews with guests ranging from small business owners to Nobel Laureates.}}</ref>

Roberts categorizes himself as a proponent of [[Classical liberalism|classical economic liberalism]]. He has said, "I believe in [[limited government]] combined with [[personal responsibility]]. So I am something of a [[libertarian]], but . . . that term comes with some baggage and some confusion."<ref>{{cite news | last = Kenney | first = Allen | title = Russ Roberts Applies Adam Smith to Modern-Day Issues | publisher = REIT.com and Real Estate Investment Trusts magazine | date = March 16, 2015 | url = https://www.reit.com/news/reit-magazine/march-april-2015/russ-roberts-applies-adam-smith-modern-day-issues | access-date = July 21, 2017}}</ref>

==Education==
Roberts was awarded a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in economics in 1975 from the [[University of North Carolina]] and [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in economics from the [[University of Chicago]] in 1981 for his thesis on the design of [[Transfer payment|government transfer programs]]<ref>[http://search.proquest.com/docview/303039469 ''A positive analysis of the design of government transfer programs'']</ref><ref name="cv">{{cite web | url = http://mercatus.org/sites/default/files/Russ_Roberts_CV.pdf | title = Russ Roberts' CV | publisher = Mercatus Center, George Mason University | accessdate = 29 December 2012}}</ref> under the supervision of [[Gary Becker]].<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.econtalk.org/archives/2012/12/chris_anderson_2.html | title = Chris Anderson on Makers and Manufacturing | publisher = [[EconTalk]] | quote =  I remember when Gary Becker, my adviser in graduate school wrote a book | accessdate = 1 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url =http://cafehayek.com/2014/05/gary-becker-rip.html | title = Gary Becker, RIP  | publisher = [[Cafe Hayek]]| accessdate = 5 May 2014}}</ref>

==Career==
Roberts has taught at George Mason University, Washington University in St. Louis (where he was the founding director of what is now the Center for Experiential Learning), the University of Rochester, Stanford University, and the University of California, Los Angeles. He is a regular commentator on business and economics for [[National Public Radio]]'s ''[[Morning Edition]]'',<ref>{{cite news | last = Noguchi | first = Yuki | title = Solving The 'Wage Puzzle': Why Aren't Paychecks Growing? | publisher = ''National Public Radio'' | date = August 2, 2018 | url = https://www.npr.org/2018/08/02/634754091/solving-the-wage-puzzle-why-aren-t-paychecks-growing}}</ref> and has written for ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''.

Roberts also blogs at ''[[Cafe Hayek]]''<ref>[http://cafehayek.com/ ''Cafe Hayek'']</ref> with [[Donald J. Boudreaux]] at George Mason University in [[Fairfax County, Virginia]].<ref>http://economics.gmu.edu/people/rrobert2</ref>

===Books about Economics===

Roberts has written a number of books which illustrate economic concepts in unconventional ways.

In 2001 he published the novel ''The Invisible Heart: An Economic Romance'', which conveys economic ideas through conversations between two fictional teachers at an exclusive high school in Washington, D.C.: one is a [[market oriented]] economics instructor, and the other is an English teacher who wants governmental protections that curb the excesses of [[Laissez-faire|unrestrained capitalism]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Book review of ''The Invisible Heart: An Economic Romance'' | publisher = Publisher's Weekly | date = February 1, 2001 | url = https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-262-18210-2 | access-date = July 29, 2017}}</ref>

In 2008, Roberts released another novel, ''The Price of Everything: A Parable of Possibility and Prosperity'', which focuses on the experiences of Ramon Fernandez, a university student and star tennis player who, as a child, accompanied his mother to the U.S. after she fled from [[Fidel Castro]]'s [[Cuba]]. Like ''The Invisible Heart'', ''The Price of Everything'' uses conversations between its main characters to address economic concepts (in this case ideas such as the [[price system]], [[spontaneous order]] and the possibility of [[price gouging]] in crisis situations).<ref>{{cite news | last = Steelman | first = Aaron | title = Bringing Life to the Dismal Science: Book review of ''The Price of Everything'' | publisher = Region Focus ("The economics magazine of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond") | date = Fall 2008 | url = https://www.richmondfed.org/~/media/richmondfedorg/publications/research/region_focus/2008/fall/pdf/book_review.pdf | access-date = July 28, 2017}}</ref>

In 2014 Roberts offered an uncommon perspective on [[Adam Smith]] in his book, ''How Adam Smith Can Change Your Life: An Unexpected Guide to Human Nature and Happiness''. The book does not discuss Smith's well known 1776 work, ''[[The Wealth of Nations]]''; it instead examines Smith's 1759 precursor to [[behavioral economics]],<ref>{{cite news | last = Brown | first = David | title = Book review of 'How Adam Smith Can Change Your Life: An Unexpected Guide to Human Nature and Happiness', by Russ Roberts | newspaper = Financial Times | location = London | date = November 23, 2014 | url = https://www.ft.com/content/25389abe-70a2-11e4-9129-00144feabdc0 | access-date = July 10, 2018}}</ref> ''[[The Theory of Moral Sentiments]]''.<ref>{{cite news | last = Gregoire | first = Carolyn | title = Before 'The Wealth Of Nations,' Adam Smith Penned The Ultimate Guide To A Moral Life | publisher = Huffington Post | date = September 9, 2014 | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/09/09/before-he-wrote-a-manifes_n_5772360.html | access-date = August 2, 2017}}</ref>
.

===Policy positions===
Roberts generally opposes [[Keynesian economics]] - particularly [[Stimulus (economics)|stimulus spending]] - saying that "it's very hard to argue in logical terms that spending money unwisely is the way to get wealthy."<ref>{{cite AV media |people = Interview of Russ Roberts by Nick Gillespie |title = Russ Roberts: Why Keynesians Always Get it Wrong (and Most Economists Too) |medium = video {quote is at 3 min. 2 sec.} |publisher = ''Reason'' magazine |date = October 11, 2012 |url = http://reason.com/reasontv/2012/10/11/russ-roberts-on-the-economic-fallicies-o}}</ref> In October 2011 he initiated a lively, extended conversation with the [[List of Nobel Memorial Prize laureates in Economics|Nobel laureate]] [[Paul Krugman]] over the effectiveness of Keynesian policies by declaring that "Krugman is a Keynesian because he wants [[Big government|bigger government]]. I'm an anti-Keynesian because I want [[Small government|smaller government]]."<ref>{{cite web | url = https://cafehayek.com/2011/10/the-evidence-for-keynesian-economics.html | title = The evidence for Keynesian economics | author = Russ Roberts | website = ''Cafe Hayek (blog)'' | date = October 11, 2011}}</ref> Krugman quoted this statement in his response and then said that "Keynesianism is not and never has been about promoting bigger government," and also that "you find conservative economists promoting quite Keynesian views of [[stabilization policy]]."<ref>{{cite web | url = https://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/12/i-am-not-your-mirror-image/ | title = I Am Not Your Mirror Image | author = Paul Krugman | website = ''The Conscience of a Liberal (blog)'' | date = October 12, 2011}}</ref> In subsequent posts, the two economists disagreed on many things, but neither one contested one central idea: Krugman was content to be characterized as a Keynesian,<ref>{{cite web | url = https://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/06/06/why-am-i-a-keynesian/ | title = Why Am I A Keynesian? | author = Paul Krugman | website = ''The Conscience of a Liberal (blog)'' | date = June 6, 2015}}</ref> while Roberts, most definitely, was not.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://cafehayek.com/2015/06/krugman-is-human-just-like-me.html | title = Krugman is human, just like me | author = Russ Roberts | website = ''Cafe Hayek (blog)'' | date = June 23, 2015}}</ref>

Roberts has urged those who formulate [[public policy]] and the economists who advise them to be more skeptical of the findings of [[Empirical research|empirical studies]],<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2017-03-15/how-to-restore-faith-in-economics | title = How to Restore Faith in Economics: Mathematical theories didn't predict the Great Recession. Research grounded in data should hold up better. | last = Smith | first = Noah | date = March 15, 2017 | publisher = Bloomberg View | access-date = August 4, 2017 | quote = [S]keptics [like Roberts] are telling us to discount the empirical evidence now pouring out of the economics profession. [They] note that many empirical studies disagree with each other, and others are later proven wrong.}}</ref> and he views ultra-specific claims by politicians that their promoted policies will produce a certain number of [[Employment|jobs]] or a certain amount of [[Economic growth|growth]] as inherently unreliable.<ref>{{cite news | last = Peterson | first = Kyle | title = When All Economics Is Political: The dismal science has too much junk science, says Russ Roberts, an evangelist for humility in a discipline where it is often hard to find. | newspaper = Wall Street Journal | date = May 13, 2016 | url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/when-all-economics-is-political-1463178093 | access-date = August 4, 2017}}</ref>

