{{Refimprove|date=September 2010}}

'''Said Akbar Khan Babrakzai''' (died 16 October 1951) was possibly an [[Afghan people|Afghan]] Pashtun, according to the government sources, and an [[Ultra-nationalist|ultra]]-[[Pashtun people|Pashtun]]<ref name="Tribune Pakistan"/> [[Pashtun nationalism|nationalist]],<ref name="Tribune Pakistan">{{cite news|last=Khuro|first=Zarrar|title=Unexplained assassinations|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/93713/unexplained-assassinations/|accessdate=9 February 2012|newspaper=Tribune Pakistan|date=December 27, 2010}}</ref> an [[Assassination|assassin]] who assassinated the [[List of Prime Ministers of Pakistan|first]] [[Prime Minister of Pakistan]], [[Liaqat Ali Khan]],<ref name="Tribune Pakistan"/> in [[Rawalpindi]] [[Punjab Province (Pakistan)|Punjab Province]], on October 16, 1951.<ref name="Tribune Pakistan"/> 

On October 16, 1951, during a public meeting, Sayed Akbar Khan shot Liaqat twice in [[Liaquat Bagh|a park]] in [[Rawalpindi]], [[Pakistan]]. The assassin was fatally shot by police officers seconds later. Liaqat was rushed to a hospital where he died. Biographical details of Sayed Akbar and the reasons why he killed Liaquat Ali Khan are not widely known.<ref>[http://www.keesings.com/search?kssp_selected_tab=article&kssp_a_id=12426n03pak "Report of Inquiry Commission on Assassination of Mr. Liaquat Ali Khan" - Keesing's]</ref><ref>[http://www.thenews.com.pk/updates.asp?id=89228 "58th death anniversary of Liaquat Ali Khan observed" - The News]</ref> It is stated in the official file on Liaquat Ali Khan that Akbar was an "Afghan national and a professional assassin."<ref>[http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_28-9-2004_pg7_47 "Did govt pay for Liaqat Ali Khan’s casket?" - Daily Times]</ref>

